    en: "A NY fair hearing is an administrative appeal of a social services decision, run by the NY Office of Administrative Hearings (OAH). The hearing rules are at 18 NYCRR Part 358. An impartial hearing officer not involved in the original decision presides. Most hearings happen by phone. The appellant may bring a lawyer, a family member, a friend, or appear alone. After the hearing, the commissioner issues a written decision — within 60 days for SNAP-only cases and within 90 days for other cases. A winning appellant has the right to enforcement of the decision; a losing appellant can seek Article 78 review in state Supreme Court."
