  whatItMeans: {
    en: "A NY fair hearing is run by the Office of Administrative Hearings within the NY Office of Temporary and Disability Assistance. The procedures are at 18 NYCRR Part 358. The process has three phases — preparation, the hearing, and the written decision. Preparation. The appellant has the right to see the full case file at the social services district before the hearing. Copies are free. The agency must make its evidence packet available at least two business days before the hearing. The appellant has the right to submit written evidence before the hearing and to bring witnesses and documents to the hearing itself. For a SNAP-related hearing, 18 NYCRR 358-5.3(a) entitles the appellant to a 30-day adjournment without any showing of good cause. For other program hearings, adjournments require good cause but are routinely granted when the appellant needs time to gather evidence or arrange representation. The hearing. An impartial hearing officer assigned by OAH presides under 18 NYCRR 358-5.6. The hearing officer must not have been involved with the action being challenged. The hearing officer's duties include opening with an explanation of the issues, administering oaths when appropriate, eliciting documents and testimony, questioning parties and witnesses as needed, and keeping the record complete. Most hearings are conducted by phone. An in-person hearing can be requested when the appeal is filed. Phone hearings are scheduled in morning (9 a.m. to 1 p.m.) or afternoon (1 p.m. to 5 p.m.) blocks. The hearing officer calls from a blocked or unknown number. If the appellant misses the call, a second attempt typically follows in 10 to 20 minutes. The social services district presents its evidence first — the notice, the underlying records, and any witness testimony. The appellant then presents — testimony, documents, and questions to the agency witness (cross-examination). Each side may call witnesses and respond to the other side's evidence. The appellant may ask the hearing officer to keep the record open briefly after the hearing to submit additional documents. Interpreters are provided at no cost. Travel, child care, and related costs can be reimbursed for in-person hearings. The written decision. Under 18 NYCRR 358-6.1, the commissioner's decision must be based exclusively on the hearing record, in writing, and must set out the issues, the relevant facts, the applicable law and regulations, and the reasons. The decision may direct specific action by the social services district. Timing is set by 18 NYCRR 358-6.4: non-food-stamp decisions within 90 days of the hearing request; SNAP-only decisions within 60 days; and if the decision raises food stamp benefits, the district must reflect the increase within 10 days of receipt. A winning appellant has the right to enforcement. If the district fails to comply, the appellant can file a compliance complaint with OAH. A losing appellant has four months to file an Article 78 petition in state Supreme Court. An appellant who misses the hearing for good cause can file a request to reopen within one year. Legal Aid Society of Rochester, LawNY, and Empire Justice Center represent low-income Monroe County appellants."
  },

